Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed as mentally ill and now she makes art on the subject - "Man should have the right to his own body"
Dozens of patient records hang from the ceiling of the Academy of Fine Arts' Project room gallery.
Each one bears Camille Auer's name.
The papers tell a multi-year story of how outsiders have written down their interpretations of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
"I wanted to share my personal medical history to make the violence of the process visible," Auer says.
By process, he refers to the process of gender reassignment.
It is often a research period lasting years, including meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral for diagnostic examinations of "gender identity disorder", which are carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, she had been using oestrogen she had ordered online and was already very well advanced in her own repair process.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through a correction process in order for her gender to be legally corrected.
The Transgender Act, i.e. the Act on the Confirmation of the Gender of Transsexuals (563/2002), obliges transgender people to undergo forced sterilisation in order to obtain the correct gender at the Population Register Centre and passport, for example.
Currently, everyone who corrects their gender is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and proof of infertility.
People have the right to make decisions about their own bodies.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the Trans Act has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight observations on the Act, and the European Court of Human Rights has a precedent obliging the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect the right to self-determination.
Finland's previous government prepared the amendment under the leadership of Susanne Huovinen, then Minister of Social Affairs and Health.
Elections came and the Finns Party entered the government.
Now the change in the law is stalled again.
These are internal political disputes that are not even related to this particular law.
"The government doesn't want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty International Finland.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient records installation, any visitor can read, for example, an interpretation of Auer by a psychologist from Tampere University Hospital's transpol.
The psychologist met with Camille Auer twice and based on them wrote a story that would define Auer's right to treatment and assistance.
The research subject's sense of reality appears to be prone to faltering.
The research subject's perception of self appears to be fragmented at the borderline level, and unstable personality traits are emphasized.
Auer did not recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to learn that I was diagnosed as mentally ill," Auer says.
Even more shocking was when Auer was not given sex reassignment treatment.
According to medical staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
Then, on February 11, 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked down the television in the transpol waiting lobby.
Later, a piece of art called Monument for the Excluded emerged from that television, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that anyone who is defined as female at birth can enlarge their breasts, but you need a diagnosis to remove your breasts," Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you perceive yourself as something other than your sex determined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not unique.
For many, the gender reassignment process is tougher for mental reasons than purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people to whom they need to justify their own existence and their right to their own sexual experience.
"It's crazy that people who are in need of support and help are denied treatment because they don't have enough resources," Auer says.
Many of those who have applied for the process have psychological symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible experiences of bullying.
Based on these, the medical staff may order that treatment cannot be started.
"Preventing treatment and help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer's first-hand exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes, "I've had suicidal thoughts my entire adult life and it's something that people usually have a hard time digesting."
Depression has been treated with medication, and when Auer started taking hormones, she felt relieved.
She had finally been able to put into words the feelings that had existed since childhood and adolescence.
Why the wide chin didn't seem to fit my body and why the pectoral muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people around him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing, using your voice and movements," she says.
Today, Auer already feels seen, she exists as a woman.
However, in the early stages of the process, random comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
What hurts the most is when loved ones misgender.
"They should know, and they know who I am, but they refuse or can't internalize it," she continues.
However, not all transgender people need physical changes.
They don't suffer from body dysphoria, a body contradiction in which the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long examination process, one cannot get official confirmation of one's own gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014 the parliament adopted a new procedure for legal gender recognition.
The new legislation is based on self-determination over legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code, stating in it that he or she feels that he or she is of the other gender.
After the six-month reflection period, the applicant confirms his or her application in writing and the Ministry issues the applicant with a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also demanded in Finland, and Auer's exhibition also encapsulates this demand.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but the exhibition is a collection of political and artistic works.
I want to believe that art still carries weight and can bring about political change, at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
