Civil rights organization issues travel warning to Missouri
The NAACP, the national civil rights organization for African Americans, has issued a travel warning for Missouri. This is due to discriminatory practices in the state and racist attacks that have taken place there.
"The NAACP's travel advisory for Missouri is effective 8/28/2017 and urges African American travelers, visitors, and locals to pay close attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state that has recently experienced numerous questionable race-based events," the organization said in a statement.
In Missouri, a recent law makes it more difficult to bring discrimination cases to court. In addition, the enforcement of state laws disproportionately affects minorities. According to the NAACP, these circumstances led to the issuing of a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They are stopped because of the color of their skin and beaten or killed," NAACP Missouri Chairman Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We haven't heard of so many cases in such a short period of time before."
The travel advisory for Missouri is the organization's first warning for the state of the United States.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee, as examples.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. He was arrested by Missouri police even though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel advisory also referred to a report by the Missouri attorney general, according to which police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white driver.
"The purpose of the travel advisory is to urge people to be vigilant and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare, for example, by bringing money to pay bail or telling relatives they're going to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, one hundred hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth-most of any state in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law that makes it harder for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU, an organization that defends constitutionally guaranteed civil rights, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws requiring police to arrest people for immigration violations. According to the organization, this increases racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the Ministry for Foreign Affairs and apply to other countries. Recently, however, NGOs have been publishing them in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
