The State has decided that supplementary pensions will not be used for rewards.
The State owns more than half of Finnair.
According to the company, the decision is in line with last year's resolution on corporate governance.
The sanctions immediately hardened the rhetoric
Not so long ago, it seemed that relations between the United States and Russia were moving from cold to warm.
US President Donald Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin, who met on the margins of the G20 meeting of industrialised countries in Hamburg, seemed to get along very well.
Since then, the atmosphere has cooled considerably.
The new economic sanctions approved by the US Congress last week and signed by Trump on Wednesday were met with bitter reactions in Russia.
The most shocking response so far has come from Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, who said the sanctions bill signed by Trump amounts to a "full-scale trade war."
Even if the Russian reactions are dismissed only as exaggerations and excesses inherent in political rhetoric, the strained relations between the United States and Russia are a fact of life after a short honeymoon after Trump's election.
In the United States, passing sanctions legislation against Russia, Iran and North Korea was not simple.
Although Congress passed the bill with considerable unanimity, it was reportedly much more difficult for the president to pass the bill.
Trump criticized the law he recently signed as "significantly flawed."
Russia in particular may have been responsible for President Trump's indignation, although the passage of a law restricting one's own powers must also have been repugnant.
As is well known, there is an investigation in the United States into both possible Russian interference in the presidential election and the Trump campaign's ties to Russia.
The strained relations between the United States and Russia are a fact of life after a short honeymoon.
As the White House staff has changed frequently and various scandalous twists and turns have been revealed almost to be updated, it seems increasingly clear that foreign policy in the United States is not conducted under the leadership of the president, but in spite of the president.
Such a situation is by no means desirable.
If the relationship with Russia is tricky in the United States, the same applies to the European Union.
In addition to economic sanctions, the tense security situation in the EU's core region of the Baltic Sea is also straining relations.
The EU has prominently highlighted the situation in Ukraine in its relations with Russia and called for the implementation of the Minsk Agreement.
Although the Union has so far remained united in its policy towards Russia, at least on the face of it, the interests of the Member States are quite different.
For a member state like Finland, which does a lot of business with Russia, economic sanctions have been a real nuisance.
The effects of the recent US sanctions law are still unclear.
There have been fears in the EU that sanctions will hamper the operations of many European companies.
In Finland, the impacts may be felt, for example, in the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project and possibly in Fennovoima's nuclear power plant project.
Acidity in Europe has been caused by the exclusion from sanctions, for example, of liquefied natural gas (LNG), which is important for the US economy.
Trade sanctions are a means of showing disapproval in world politics.
Economic sanctions, however, must be well thought out and specific.
Otherwise, they will easily do more harm than good.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Trump's White House now has its sights set on the Statue of Liberty
Interfering with statues is the surest sign of regime change.
The Americans know this as well as anyone else: the Iraqis, together with American soldiers, toppled the statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the chief ideologists of the Trump administration, knew very well what he was doing in a heated debate with CNN's Jim Acosta. The Statue of Liberty came under attack from Miller over a verbal dispute over the president's proposal to drastically reduce legal immigration.
Miller didn't exactly criticize the statue itself.
If he had done so, he would have been attacked by huge hordes of cruise organizers and figures imitating the Statue of Liberty.
He attacked the significance of the statue, especially the fact that in 1903 a poem by Emma Lazarus was added to the statue's pedestal – 17 years after the statue's completion.
Here's how Miller berated Acosta: "I don't want to go into history now, but the Statue of Liberty is... Symbol of American freedom that illuminates the whole world.
The poem was added later and does not belong to the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller was not wrong per se, but it is not just history, as he himself said.
Essential are Lazarus' touching words, the only ones of its kind, in which the state calls not only immigrants but "the poorest of the poor": "Your tired, your poor, / Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free, / The wretched refuse of your teeming shore."
The poem is now more relevant than ever.
Miller was by no means engaged in literary criticism. He made it clear that "the poorest of the poor" are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The controversy over the significance of the Statue of Liberty is part of a broader political and cultural controversy over the significance of the United States.
After his death, Lazarus' friends campaigned for the poem to be mounted on the statue's pedestal. They were well aware that the act was strongly political.
The purpose of the statue was to embody the connections between French and American republicanism with a classic metaphor, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in his poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the deported.
Associating the poem with the image was an ingenious feminist coup d'état and a devastating attack on American nationalism.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to change it back to its original.
Rush Limbaugh – a mouthpiece who can now be seen as something of a harbinger of Trump – argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is not an invitation to anyone, but an early forerunner of neoconservatives carrying the U.S. torch into a world shrouded in darkness: "Lady Liberty will step forward.
He takes the freedom to torch from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch does not show the way to the United States."
Rarely, Limbaugh was partially right.
The meaning of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on your point of view.
Lazarus saw it like poor and exhausted but hopeful immigrants from the deck of a ship after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people seeking protection and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty comforts by giving hope and welcome.
And that's definitely not what Miller and Trump want.
Their torch does not show the way, but fuels the flames of hatred, their only source of strength.
2017 World Championships in Athletics: Neil Black praises Scottish members of the UK national team
