Block critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity is.
Americans loved George Washington, but newspapers soon began criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism certainly irritated,
But he did not silence his critics.
"If freedom of speech is abolished, we may be led foolish and silent like sheep to be slaughtered," Washington said in 1783.
That brings us to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff have removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked their authors.
The American Civil Rights Union sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff considers the challenge unfounded, and the attitude was dismissive even online.
"What does it matter? This is just Facebook," many commented.
But it matters,
especially in the Hogan case.
Hogan is the amazingly popular Republican governor of the Democrat-controlled state.
He has received the second best ratings among 50 governors for his activities.
Hogan is not responsive to hotheads.
He has led the state steadfastly and held fast to principles.
He has also competently used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his constituents, posting a photo of his head balding during chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking users entering the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax revenue.
Hogan's spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor's actions in an interview with The Washington Post. According to him, it was just a matter of moderating comments.
However, labeling commenters as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to their chosen leaders. They were not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They reported that their comments were respectful, considerate and matter-of-fact.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his commentary; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile and asked a question about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not addressed hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in comments to the Washington Post story.
"I also find it unacceptable that when more people comment on the same issue, they are immediately seen as somehow organised and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens."
The governor's staff called the comments a "concerted attack." Someone else might call them to promote issues that are considered important.
In the age of Facebook, communication is easy to manage by blocking a reviewer or removing a critical comment.
In the old days, staff should have been sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or to arrest and silence demonstrators.
In reality, however, it is the same thing, now only digitally.
Hogan isn't the first public official to be accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
Twitter users blocked by President Trump have sued him.
The first major decision on the subject was taken last week in Virginia.
According to Alexandria District Court Judge James C. Cacheris, the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment to the U.S. Constitution by blocking voters on Facebook.
And the American Civil Rights Association went to talk to Kentucky Republican Governor Matt Bevin about the use of Twitter and Facebook.
This should not be difficult.
In Washington's day, low postage rates had a similar effect to today's Internet.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and Washington was pounded by anonymous writers.
Already at that time there were trolls.
The pseudonyms Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters to newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticizing the Jay Treaty, i.e. the U.S.-Britain Cooperation, Trade and Maritime Agreement. This is according to documents collected by the Papers of George Washington online project.
However, he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of expression, opinion and debate are the cornerstones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
Summer feeding of birds should be stopped immediately
Samples have been received from about half a dozen places, as well as online advertisements from two or three.
Most of them have come from Southern and Southwest Finland, but then also individual ones from Haapavesi and Seinäjoki," says Senior Researcher Marja Isomursu from Evira.
Greenfinches have died from a parasitic disease called trichomonosis.
It is caused by a protozoan known as Trichomonas gallinae.
It has previously been known to strike pigeons, especially bunnies.
In the 2000s, however, the disease also began to be detected in finches.
In 2009, it really kicked in.
At that time, trichomonosis caused a major collapse in the Finnish greenfinch population, after which the populations of the species have been recovering.
There have now been sick greenfinches, but at least not yet on a large scale," says Juha Honkala, Museum Manager at the Finnish Museum of Natural History (Luomus) at the University of Helsinki.
It is to be feared that the previous epidemic of greenfinches will recur again if something is not done.
What needs to be done now is a very simple thing that everyone can do: stop feeding birds in the summer immediately.
More on that later.
