In Säkylä, possible indoor air problems in the barracks were investigated
In Säkylä, no indoor air problems have been found in the barracks building of the Pori Brigade's signal company, at least for the time being, the brigade said on Thursday.
Indoor air quality studies are still ongoing.
The investigation began when a man who had interrupted his military service for health reasons thought that his health had deteriorated due to poor indoor air in the barracks.
According to Lieutenant Colonel Mika Holma, Chief of Staff of the Pori Brigade, no problems have been detected in the health situation of other conscripts.
It turned out that this was an isolated incident and that the others who served in that unit had no health problems.
Every report is taken seriously and we wanted to get to the bottom of this.
At the moment, we are not aware of any indoor air problems," Holma says.
The brigade's press release says that due to the arrival batch in July, goods had to be moved to the barracks, which may have caused a temporary increase in dustiness.
Because of this, the air may have seemed stuffy," Holma says.
Poverty and death in Indonesia's golden land
Bardina Degei does not use a stove in cooking.
He rarely uses the boiler either.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in Indonesia's troubled province of Papua. When she prepares dinner, she usually puts the sweet potato — locally "nota" — directly into the hearth.
After half an hour, the burnt sweet potato is eaten voraciously with bare, unwashed hands.
There is no furniture in Degei's home. She sits on a muddy ground floor, where she usually also does her daily chores, such as doing laundry in the murky water fetched from a nearby swamp.
The posts of the toilet are supplied by a bucket in a room without a ceiling.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives and is not assigned to take care of the fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed and many drink a lot. In addition, it is necessary to take into account the military.
"No one dares to walk in the village after five o'clock in the evening," Degei says.
This is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 village elders were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control of the region and blocks foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotal is remote and dreary. The journey starts with an hour-and-a-half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabare and continues with a stomach-wrenching five-hour drive in a rental car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, the corrugated tin roofs of which have been stained yellow-brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, let alone journalists and foreigners.
Before the advent of Christian missionaries, the me Pago tribesmen of Papua worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
There have also been other changes.
"We didn't have clothes like this," Degei says. She means her colorful, hand-woven wraparound headdress, dark skirt, and brightly colored blouse.
"We used to only have leaves to cover our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia. 28% of its inhabitants live below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also the gold land of Indonesia.
Paniai is a highland area about the size of New Jersey with 153,000 inhabitants. Just about a hundred kilometers from Paniia is Grasberg, the world's largest and most lucrative gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine provided Freeport with $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
For the Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
The New York Times revealed in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and local military units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004. Individual officers were paid up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater sovereignty threaten this source of income and are mercilessly silenced.
According to human rights activists, since 1969 the Indonesian army has killed more than 500 000 Papuans and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, massacres in the highlands of Papua tribes in the 1970s assumed genocidal proportions.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3 900 people in peaceful protests in the region.
The 2016 We Will Lose Everything report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane includes accounts of previous years' atrocities, including extrajudicial executions, torture – rape and electrocution being particularly popular methods – and relentless attacks on peaceful protest.
"It's hard to count the number of victims because there are cases every week," said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Christians make up 83% of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, but the demographic is changing as Muslims move from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi in search of a better livelihood.
Javanese warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable mix in peanut sauce.
It's hard for locals to compete.
"Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at the market cheaper than locals," says Abeth You, 24, who hails from Paniia and moved to the provincial capital for work.
"Local women lost their customers."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – pledged in his 2014 election campaign to address injustices and human rights abuses in Papua.
Papua is made up of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Paniai, on his way to Jakarta's presidential palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokow in 2014 and expected him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You says.
Paniia experienced something of a nadir just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by a campfire in Enarotal on 7.12.2014 when two Indonesian soldiers on motorcycles appeared from the darkness.
The frightened children told the soldiers to wear headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark. According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned with four soldiers.
According to the accounts of victims and witnesses, drunken soldiers apprehended the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Thus, one of the soldiers fired at the children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of the assault.
A couple of hours later, the State Election Commission building near the scene was set on fire, and the next day things began to happen.
About a thousand Papuans – young men and women and children – gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and army command center to demand justice.
Carrying hunting bows for festive occasions, they began performing the traditional waita dance of the Papuan me Pago tribe, which involves dancing in a ring and imitating birdsong.
Some of the demonstrators began stoned police and army buildings.
As the atmosphere heated up, the soldiers received orders on the internal radio system: "If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them dead." The information is based on an official document seen by TIME magazine that has not been made public to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, resident leader of the Kego Koto area, sensed that the situation was getting out of hand and asked the crowd to calm down and return to their homes.
No one wanted to listen anymore.
"When I turned around, I was shot in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who shot him, but the bullet came from the ranks of soldiers.
"Several shots were fired in the crowd."
Alfius Youw was shot three times. His cousin witnessed the shootings.
"I ran up to him and made sure it was indeed him," Yohanes told TIME magazine sadly. Like many Indonesians, he uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Papua Police Superintendent Yotje Mende told reporters that the police were only "protecting" the police station because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua police spokesman Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"Then it's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
News of the killings reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an emotional speech in Jayapura expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and pledging that the violence in Papua would be addressed.
"I want the incident to be investigated immediately so that something like this never happens again."
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he would launch investigations into human rights violations outside the judicial system.
However, he immediately began to retract his speeches.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago,
In the 1990s and early 2000s.
The most important thing is that we have decided to investigate the violations, but for that we need certain processes," he said.
In an interview with TIME magazine in Jakarta on 5.6.2017, Wiranto had already changed his mind. He said he did not intend to open investigations in Papua.
"Everything will be sorted out in court," he said.
The UN accuses Wiranto of "crimes against humanity." The crimes relate to the deaths of more than a thousand people in East Timor's bloody independence referendum in 1999. Wiranto told TIME magazine that 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua have already been solved, including those in Paniai.
The families of the victims of Paniai are greeted with dark disbelief at the allegations.
"I've been interviewed four times in the last three years, but things haven't progressed in any way," Yohanes says.
"I'm already tired of this."
She says she still lives in fear, even though it's been years since the incident.
"Yes, I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me. I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirms that the Spaniels do not dare to discuss the incident.
He says he had been beaten by soldiers after helping bury four of the victims.
"The soldiers sought me out after the victims were buried," he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in Paniai's neighboring Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 injured in an altercation between villagers and the manager of a construction company that began when the manager refused to take a man who had lost consciousness to hospital. Children were also among the injured.
The man who needed hospital treatment was 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who had been caught in the water while fishing in a nearby river. He died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers demonstrated at a construction site in front of the company's office.
According to police, villagers stoned police officers who responded with warning shots.
However, according to locals, a mobile police unit of the Indonesian paramilitary police opened fire on the crowd, killing one villager.
"We are terrified. We are afraid of retaliation," said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being brought in for treatment.
"I've been hiding at home for two days."
Deiyai's parliament has called for the police officers who fired shots to be held accountable and for the mobile police unit to be pulled out of the area.
Paniai has always been a sticking point for the Indonesian government.
The lack of real development feeds the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes living in Papua's lush central highlands.
Many have joined the Papuan Liberation Movement (OPM), a rebel army that claims to defend the rights of Papuans through sporadic attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian army soldiers.
Some of OPM's leaders are Panic, such as Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
The army has responded to the rebellion by arbitrarily arresting and detaining thousands of people in Paniai in the name of 'safeguarding national sovereignty'.
Some of those arrested never return.
Among the Papuans, Paniai is known as a "sad, forgotten place."
Poverty feeds discontent.
There is little rice for sale in Enarotal, and even that is too expensive for the locals,
Like bread.
People grow their own food: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is women's work, and one woman can be responsible for four or five sweet potato fields.
Most of the harvest is for the family, and the rest is sold at the market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 rupees (75 cents).
Over time, disparities in the livelihoods of locals and migrants have widened, and the number of migrants has increased since new routes were opened to Nabare Airport.
Jobs are scarce and tend to go to better-educated and wealthier migrants than locals.
Only a few people in Papua have enough capital and know-how to run their own business competitively.
"Young people don't want to stay in the village because there are no jobs and no money here," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Remote Papua receives little attention around the world.
In addition, restrictions on international news coverage remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua despite being granted rare permission to photograph. The official reason was the inability to cooperate with local institutions.
Phelim Kine, Asia deputy director at Human Rights Watch, said Jokowi had not kept his election promises. He has not increased transparency or promoted development by removing restrictions on news coverage.
"Journalists covering Indonesia's troubled easternmost provinces, Papua and West Papua, face new risks: visa denial and blacklisting," Kine said in a statement.
The lack of freedom of action for the press means that pressure on the Indonesian Government is exerted only by Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands – called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "numerous and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also traditionally supported the Papuan liberation movement.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Arrmanatha Nasir denied the allegations and told reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia remains a democracy with freedom of the press, so it would be difficult to cover up evidence of human rights violations."
The locals want foreign governments to intervene.
When an official Dutch delegation led by Human Rights Ambassador Kees Van Bar visited Jayapura on 4.5.2017, locals broke their silence and expressed their desire for freedom, according to a source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
Indonesia has a presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokow anymore.
"Jokowi means well, but he is surrounded by people who are implicated in the shooting scene in Paniai," says Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Yokowi to know the situation of the Spaniels, who live under the rule of a greedy and unpredictable army, deprived of deprivation and poverty, virtually deprived of health services and educational opportunities.
According to Gobai, the Spaniards, like other Papuans, consider the votes they cast for Jokow to be a "debt" that must be repaid.
"They don't want money. They just want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the relatives of the victims of the Paniai shooting demonstration once again demonstrated symbolic resistance: they buried one of the victims in the country opposite the police station and army office.
They know that they may never get justice, but at least they will not let those responsible forget their crimes.
"My family members were killed," Yacobus says with his head bowed.
"What else could we do?"
