In the United States, more than 20 percent of air passengers take prohibited items on board, survey reveals
A survey of air travelers reveals that more than 20 percent of U.S. passengers had knowingly or unknowingly taken prohibited items onto airplanes past U.S. Federal Transportation Safety Administration (TSA) checkpoints. At least six percent of the passengers had knives or other objects with blades that they did not know were prohibited.
Less than one per cent said they only found out afterwards that they had mistakenly transported weapons, ammunition or explosives.
More than a thousand passengers responded to the survey and it was conducted by the charter airline Stratos Jet Charters. The results also reveal that young passengers are more likely to defy the rules.
Of the passengers who knowingly violated TSA rules, 19.7 percent were Generation Y and less than 15 percent belonged to Generation X.
Most commonly, the rules were violated by taking food and liquids on board the aircraft.
More than three per cent admitted to knowingly taking objects with blades to an aircraft. In addition, 2.2% of women and 3.7% of men said they had knowingly taken prohibited drugs on board an aircraft.
The survey included travelers from all over the United States. The company that conducted the survey wanted to find out how many people had accidentally taken smuggling goods past security and how many had done so knowingly.
Not surprisingly, those who travel the most are also most likely to take contraband goods past security – knowingly or unknowingly.
But as the company that conducted the survey notes, TSA's guidelines are quite complex and confusing.
Passengers often do not know what liquids are allowed on board the aircraft and how much.
So it's no surprise that most TSA seizures are liquids.
For some time, there was also a belief that you were not allowed to take books on board an aircraft.
Liquids may be taken on domestic flights, but not on international flights.
Scott Pruitt, director of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, reversed his decision to delay Obama-era decisions to reduce emissions
A day after 15 states sued EPA Director Scott Pruitt, Pruitt reversed his earlier decision to delay the implementation of decisions taken during the Obama administration to reduce smog-causing emissions.
According to Pruitt, the change shows that the agency he heads is more responsive than previous administrations to the needs of state environmental policymakers.
Pruitt did not say a word about the lawsuit filed against his earlier decision in federal appeals court.
Länder should start complying with the 2015 ground-level ozone requirement from 1.10.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the implementation of the decisions by a year to give his agency more time to review the plan because the agency "does not want to interfere in local decision-making or hamper economic growth."
Pruitt was the attorney general for the state of Oklahoma before President Donald Trump appointed him director of the EPA. Pruitt is known as an opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since coming to Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly tried to block or delay the implementation of decisions opposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's abrupt change of heart is the latest setback in Pruitt's plan to relax regulations.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington, D.C., ruled that the EPA chief exceeded his authority in an attempt to delay the implementation of the Obama administration's decision on oil and gas companies. The decision obligated the companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement Wednesday evening, Pruitt argued that his U-turn on ozone regulations will only strengthen EPA's collaboration with states in the complex process of meeting the new requirements on schedule.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines and then waited for activist groups and others to sue to reach an agreement on timelines," Pruitt said. In his previous position, he sued the Environment Agency more than ten times.
"We do not believe in regulation through litigation and take deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously the regulation governing our activities and the powers it gives us."
However, the EPA statement said Pruitt can still use his "powers to delay the execution of decisions, as well as his other legal powers," to ensure that regulations "are justified and based on the best available information."
Republicans are pushing for a broader change in ozone regulations in Congress.
The bill, passed last month, aims to delay the implementation of the 2015 decisions by at least eight years.
The proposal has not yet been voted on in the Senate.
New York State Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group will continue to press.
"The EPA's change of heart as a result of our lawsuits is a significant victory for the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans exposed to the direct effects of smog in their communities," Schneiderman said.
In addition to New York, the lawsuit included California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is created when emissions from cars, power plants, oil refineries and chemical plants, for example, react to sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing difficulties in sensitised groups of people. It is also a contributing factor to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists rejoiced at Pruitt's surprising change of direction.
"It's disturbing how much pressure it took for the guy in charge of the air we breathe to use common sense," says Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to fight the Trump administration, whose ideological goal is to act on the terms of polluters and other self-interested groups."
