Georgia massacre: Activists re-stage racist lynching in hopes of justice
A Ford Mercury car passes the crowd in the small town of Monroe in rural Georgia and continues toward the small Moore's Ford Bridge.
There are four black passengers and a white driver in the car. Four armed men block the road before the car reaches the bridge.
The leader of the group, a middle-aged man dressed in a striped suit, takes a deep breath from his cigar and peers through the windshield.
Passengers are scared.
"Roger, n---u!" the man groans.
"Get out of the car!"
Shouts break the silence as a young black man is pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this shocking event is just a re-enactment that aired on 22.7.2017.
However, the sighs of shock are genuine when the noose is threaded around "Roger's" neck.
Since 2005, human rights groups have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to re-stage the events of 1946. At the time, two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey, were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan.
No one has been charged with the murders.
"It's baffling that no one has been arrested in all these years — even though the murderers live among us and many need to know who they are," says Tyrone Brooks, who helps arrange the re-stage.
"It is a stain on history, but above all it is a burden that weighs on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old civil rights activist and former Georgia congressman.
For him, the re-staging is a startling call to action. It also reminds Monroe residents that the wrong has never been righted.
"We want those responsible to be brought to justice. We want things to finally come to an end, and we want to recover from the grief and reconcile, but most of all we want justice," Brooks says.
"We cannot recover and reconcile until we get justice."
The coroner covers the body of the victim who died in the Georgia massacre on 27.7.1946.
According to FBI documents obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected of lynching.
However, no one was charged with murder.
Although the perpetrators have been at large for decades, activists say the motives for the lynching have always been known to locals: politics and sex.
In 1946, the Supreme Court ruled that blacks in the state of Georgia were allowed to vote for the first time in a presidential election. The Supreme Court handed down its decision in April, and elections were held in the summer.
According to the FBI, there was an incident around the election in which Roger Malcom, a black tenant farmer, stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, during a fight apparently involving Malcom's wife, Dorothy.
According to Brooks, the town rumored that Hester had been having an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was expecting a child for her.
According to FBI records, on 7/25/1946, influential white landowner Loy Harrison paid Malcom's $600 bail, in exchange for which he was released from prison.
On the way home, Malcom and Dorothy were accompanied by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
The mob stopped their car before Moore's Ford Bridge.
"It turns out that Harrison ordered and orchestrated the murders," the FBI report states.
"It is also evident that there was a conspiracy between state and local authorities. The authorities were complicit in the murders and destroyed the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
"It was a suffrage killing," he says.
"They were murdered because they wanted to send a message to black people that the same thing would happen to them if they were going to vote."
Cassandra Greene has been directing a re-enactment of the Georgia massacre for nearly a decade.
The performance is extremely realistic and captivating. It is a description of the shocking racism that many would like to believe has disappeared from today's United States.
It's hard to watch the show, but even harder not to watch, which Greene says is the intention.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because we'd have to face our own dark sides," the director says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you can't hear me or don't want to hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year's show began in June. On the first day, about 30 actors—a dozen black and twenty white—gathered to listen to Greene's routine summary of the show.
Wade Marbaugh serves as Greene's assistant director.
He has played the local Ku Klux Klan leader in the re-set for years, but the role is always difficult and repulsive.
"I feel dirty because I'm not myself," Marbaugh says.
"However, it is important that this aspect of history is also highlighted so that it never happens again."
Across the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, aka Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, practice their lines.
The show begins with a scene where Malcom yells and nudges Hester. He is furious that Hester has had an affair with Dorothy.
"Didn't you hear? I said get out of my lands, n---u!"
Rascona aka Hester answers.
Then leaves the beat.
And then everyone (at least all the black actors) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the hardest.
"What?!" Rascona asks.
He is confused.
"Did I accidentally hit too hard?" he asks.
"No," Greene chuckles.
"I just don't think whites used the word n---u."
"Yes," another black actor confirms.
"It's slang. You have to use a longer version."
The subject matter of the performance is unpleasant, but the room is invaded by a spirit of friendship.
Everyone wants to succeed, and not just for the sake of the show. They want to honour the memory of those who died.
The scene starts all over again.
Now Rascona's words are catching on.
No one laughs.
The re-staging ends quickly and violently.
Shouting, gunshots – and silence.
A woman dressed in a black funeral costume stands beside the bodies and sings Billie Holiday's "Strange Fruit."
His voice breaks with every other word.
A few dozen meters away, about fifty spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
Almost exactly half of the audience is black and half white.
Among them is a couple who have come to see the show from Ithaca, New York, but most are locals.
Under Brooks' guidance, they have visited the graves of the victims in the oppressive humidity of Georgia.
The murders have gone from story to reality. The atmosphere at the venue is heavy.
After the singing performance, Greene calls the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children squat down to watch fake blood and motionless corpses and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," the little boy mutters, as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Greene thanks the audience.
The actors who played the lynchers take off their cloaks and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man who played the local Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Rascona hugs the two actors and then bursts into tears after a tough performance.
"It's okay," the woman involved in the performance comforts.
"We know you're not him.
You did this for a good reason."
Later, the audience and actors gather for a joint dinner.
A white couple from Altanta has a lively conversation about the show with a black couple they have just met.
Denise Duplinski struggles to find words when describing the feelings evoked by the performance.
"It's hard to listen to horrible words and watch the horrible things that people say and do that look like you — just because they look like you," she says.
"What made me aware of the show was that lynchings are still happening," he added. "They're just called arrests."
Across the room, Brooks recalls the development of civil rights to listeners sitting at the same table.
He says he has already started planning next year's show.
"Re-staging is a powerful experience because it portrays the horrors we've experienced, but it's also an educational experience," Brooks says.
"Its message is that this can happen again if we don't learn from it.
Those who do not know their history are doomed to repeat it."
Hanging vegetables in stores is a stir: This is how much you can actually save by removing "extra parts"
