Then there are smaller brokerage firms, without naming names, whose personnel seem to have avoided completing degrees," Savikko says.
According to him, there are "a few" such brokerage firms.
According to Saviko, 13,000–14,000 people have completed the APV1 degree since 2000 and about 3,000 people have completed the more demanding APV2 degrees recommended for investment advisors.
Some brokerage firms consider having a degree to be an advantage.
Many other industries have significantly stricter competence requirements.
Savikko says that the recommendation of the Financial Services Finland requires the completion of APV degrees, because then competence related to the investment sector is ensured.
According to Statistics Finland, financial and investment advisors earn an average of several thousand euros per month, including commissions, fringe benefits and performance-based bonuses.
The average earnings for regular working hours of monthly-paid employees are approximately EUR 5,300.
On average, men working in these tasks earn good EUR 5,900 per month and women over EUR 4,500.
The tenth of the highest earners earns, on average, around EUR 8,100.
One-tenth of the highest earning men earn over EUR 9,000 per month or more, one-tenth of the highest earning women earn EUR 6,400 or more.
Investment advice in accordance with the Act on Investment Services can only be provided by an authorised company.
Until now, self-regulation has been relied on at the employee and task level.
According to the FSA, its audit revealed individual cases where the professional skills and qualifications of the investment adviser were not sufficient based on the adviser's activities.
In principle, you can also act as a seller of investment products, even if your professional skills and qualifications are at a low level.
In principle, the situation in this regard has been wild and free.
Many other industries have considerably stricter competence requirements, Savikko says.
According to Saviko, this will be tightened from the beginning of next year with the new Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II).
It requires that each company is responsible for ensuring that the personnel providing investment services are sufficiently competent.
The Financial Supervisory Authority, on the other hand, will be given the authority to determine what needs to be done.
Marko Hovi, Market Supervisor at the FSA, says that one of the clear changes to the current situation is the regulation on the competence and experience requirements for investment advisors and sellers of investment products.
