New age test results for Swedish asylum seekers published
The latest results of medical age tests for asylum seekers in Sweden have been published. The results of tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80% of those tested were determined to be over 18 years old. However, not everyone considers the tests reliable.
The Swedish National Forensic Agency began testing earlier this year.
The tests can be used to estimate the age of asylum seekers more accurately than before. The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the real age of applicants claiming to be minors.
So far, the Finnish Immigration Service has commissioned 6,880 tests, and the Forensic Office has now published the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were carried out between mid-March and late July 2017.
Of those tested, 80 per cent, i.e. asylum seekers in 2002, were determined to be over 18 years of age. In addition, in 25 cases, the Bureau of Forensic Medicine determined that the test subject was "possibly 18 years of age or older."
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker was "possibly under 18 years of age".
Tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Office of Forensic Medicine says that the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"The numbers are pretty consistent. There are no big differences from previous months' statistics," he told The Local.
Although a large percentage of applicants were determined to be over 18 years old, that does not necessarily mean that applicants lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases there were "indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older."
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests involves taking X-rays of wisdom teeth and magnetic resonance images of the knee joints. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticised.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing human biological maturity. The assessment can be used to determine whether the person has reached puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I've had reason to think about it, and I don't think the method used is the right one.
Determining biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he told Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson from the Forensic Medical Office defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, the risk of defining a child as an adult is low.
The risk is greatest in a situation where the test subject will soon turn 18. Then the risk is about 10 percent."
