Regulations restricting the spending of European football clubs do not prevent Neymar from being transferred from Barcelona, Spain, to Paris Saint-Germain in France. It is football's most expensive transfer ever.
Its possible consequences for Paris Saint-Germain (PSG) will be decided by UEFA, which regulates European football, which could prevent teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League.
In 2011, UEFA introduced fair play financial rules. According to them, PSG must be able to prove that Neymar's transfer has been financed without major losses.
Barcelona were paid €222 million to terminate the Brazilian's contract, and Neymar's annual salary at the new club runs into tens of millions of dollars.
Neymar's transfer to France involves a wide range of financial considerations.
PSG will have no trouble paying Neymar's transfer fee and adding him to their all-star roster, as the club is funded by Qatar's oil-rich royal family.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums of money on the acquisition of players, but these must be balanced by real sources of income so that football-related business is not loss-making.
The Fair Play Financial Code was drawn up on the initiative of Michel Platini, a Frenchman elected President of UEFA in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini felt that the pursuit of success through debt was cheating and led to serious problems if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of fair play financial rules shifted from club debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that Roman Abramovich's business model, which was first used at Chelsea in 2003, became significantly more difficult to implement. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
The current three-year evaluation period of the Fair Play Financial Code runs until 2018. During this period, clubs are allowed to make a loss of up to €30 million.
Although Platini was scandalously forced to step down as UEFA president in 2015, his successor, Aleksander Ceferin, also wants to curb the clubs' reckless spending.
"The fair play rules are still in place and we will continue to apply them in the future," Andrea Traverso, UEFA's head of financial rules for fair play, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of his contract in a lump sum, they can spread the amount over the entire duration of his new contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be recorded as an annual expense of €44.4 million for the next five years.
Based on fair play financial rules, the first sanctions were handed out in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Abu Dhabi-funded Manchester City.
PSG was fined €60 million, which was later reduced to €20 million. In addition, the club was ordered to limit its Champions League squad to 21 players for the 2014–15 season instead of the usual 25.
UEFA monitors clubs that may try to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their income through companies linked to club owners.
For example, if a Qatari company supports PSG but the value of the aid is considered to be above the normal market level, UEFA will not count the aid as actual revenue.
This happened when UEFA decided in 2014 that the Qatar Tourism Authority's support for PSG was excessive.
It has also emerged that part of Neymar's earnings at PSG could be funded by fees from Qatar's 2022 FIFA World Cup organising committee.
However, PSG and the organising committee have denied that Neymar is being made an ambassador for the World Cup. It would be very easy for UEFA to reveal such an arrangement.
Due to PSG's previous sanctions, UEFA is monitoring attempts to circumvent the rules even more closely than usual.
Sources familiar with the situation said on Thursday that UEFA had not held talks with PSG over a transfer for Neymar.
The sources gave an interview to the Associated Press on the condition that their identities would not be revealed as they were not authorised to discuss PSG's situation.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG's turnover for the period 2015–2016 was €542.4 million and operating profit exceeded €10 million.
Last period's financial statements have not yet been published.
PSG expect Neymar's arrival to attract new sponsors and boost sales of club merchandise and jerseys.
The club estimates that its turnover will increase by at least 30 percent with Neymar's contract.
Clearly irritated by the departure of one of the best players in the world, the Spanish league tried to complicate Neymar's transfer. It allegedly violated the financial rules of fair play.
"This is a clear case of financial doping, both for the club and for the state," Spanish league president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS. By state, he was referring to PSG's Qatari ownership.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger also has reservations about state funding of the football club. Arsenal is owned by an American sports tycoon.
"The incident is the result of ownership that has completely changed the landscape of football over the past 15 years," Wenger said Thursday.
"Anything is possible after the state owns a football team.
It will be very difficult to comply with the financial rules of fair play. There are so many interests involved in a famous player representing the state."
