Small Circle Nostalgia: Wet Hot American Summer and Comrade Detective
The story simultaneously yearns for the characters' glory days in the '80s and grunge of the '90s (at the time, David Wain and Michael Showalter were making the brilliant sketch series The State for MTV) and its own time – 2001, before Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, Paul Rudd, and the show's other stars moved on to bigger things in their careers.
As a cultural product, it is both a parody and a depiction of the constant reminiscence we are stuck in in the Facebook era.
As a commercial product, it feels outdated.
First Day of Camp worked surprisingly well, and not only because of its absurd humor (among other things, it told the backstory of a can of vegetables speaking in the voice of H. Jon Benjamin).
The crux of the joke is that middle-aged actors play lustful teenagers approaching adulthood. Emphasizing it makes the impossibility of reaching for the past part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, in which adults play adults, is less emotional and its parody is more fragmented: it parodies 90s stalker films such as the horror film The Hand That Rocks the Cradle.
At one point, one of the characters digs out an Apple Powerbook, inline skates and "other stuff from 1991".
Many of the stories are the same as before.
The kind-hearted Coop (Michael Showalter) is now a writer, but still hasn't gotten over Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
And there's a crazy plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Michael Showalter) with his partner in crime George H. W. Bush (aptly played by Michael Ian Black).
As always in such series, the best thing is the side paths.
It's especially fun to see the ever-young Paul Rudd wearing a tassel of beards under his lower lip, aka Matt Dillon's "soul patch" from the movie Singles. Andy, the king of the camp, played by Rudd, is starting to be an old guy.
Moments of random madness might propel this series into flight as a kind of recursive Seven Up! series until it reaches its obvious conclusion: Wet Hot American Summer – Twenty Years Later. In its final scene, a group of friends goes to the premiere of Wet Hot American Summer.
Amazon's Comrade Detective series, on the other hand, appeals to a different kind of nostalgia: The Americans' Cold War spirit, Atomic Blonde, and even the GLOW wrestling imagery where East meets West.
The comedy series was created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka and directed by Rhys Thomas. It is made into a Romanian police drama of the 1980s, in which a Bucharest cop fight for truth, atheism and Marxism-Leninism.
Starring the tough-faced Gregor and idealistic Iosef are Florin Piersic Jr and Corneliu Ulici. Their lines have been dubbed in English by Channing Tatum (executive producer of the series) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a great idea,
But it is not much more than that.
There are some good visual jokes in the series (cops spend time watching chess on TV the same way Americans watch football).
It features a cast of famous voice actors, including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny. Spotting them makes for a fun game.
However, Comrade Detective gets too caught up in the imitation of clumsy socialist drama – there's a killer hiding behind a Reagan mask, for example. That's why the series often really starts to feel like clumsy propaganda.
Six long episodes are too long, and the humor of the series is neither fast nor rich enough.
In a nutshell, the series might work better as agitprop satire, for example when Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the U.S. Embassy and there are always two fat men in the lobby devouring hamburgers.
The message to the imagined communist public is that Western culture can make everything a consumer commodity and fast food.
The fictional Romanian creators of the series were not wrong: we devoured our own recent history and theirs as well.
