Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged as economic growth has been sluggish and easing inflation has put an end to speculation of rate hikes.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish. The bank postponed interest rate hikes as families' incomes come under increasing pressure.
The decision-makers of the central bank's monetary policy committee voted 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25%. There was even less support for raising interest rates this month due to sluggish economic growth.
In its quarterly inflation bulletin, the bank lowered its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and its forecast for 2018 to 1.6%. It also warned that household incomes are under increasing pressure as inflation is expected to continue to accelerate to close to three per cent in the autumn.
However, according to the bank, interest rate hikes will be needed in the coming years to curb inflation fuelled by Brexit. In addition, the bank indicated that borrowing costs may need to be increased more than expected by the financial markets.
In addition, the members of the committee decided to cancel part of the massive economic package that began implementation a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The bank will end the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide an additional £15 million in low-cost financing to banks through the scheme, totalling £115 million.
The minutes of the Bank's interest rate decision state: "According to the forecast of the Monetary Policy Commission, the slow development of GDP will continue in the coming years as the fall in real household incomes reduces consumption."
On interest rates, the bank reiterated that "some tightening of monetary policy" is needed to curb inflation "somewhat broadly" than market expectations.
The market is currently forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increases will be "gradual" and "limited".
In May, the bank forecast growth of 1.9% for this year and 1.7% for next year.
It now kept its growth forecast for 2018 at 1.8%.
The pound weakened against the dollar and euro as a result of the news.
Against the dollar, the pound depreciated 0.5% to $1.31. Against the euro, it weakened by 0.4 per cent and stood at EUR 1.11.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged came after weaker-than-expected growth rates dampened increased expectations of rate hikes. GDP grew by 0.3 per cent in the second quarter and by 0.2 per cent in the first quarter.
The bank expects growth to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation survey offered little hope to households suffering from soaring inflation and meagre wage increases. According to the bank, the situation will get even worse before it gets better.
The bank added that monetary policy "cannot prevent" a drop in income in the next few years. However, it expects wage developments to recover "significantly" at the end of the three-year forecast horizon.
The economy will also be boosted by strong growth in demand for British products as a result of the weak pound. It offsets part of the effect of the fall in private consumption.
The decision comes a year after interest rates were cut to 0.25% following a shocking EU referendum that plunged the pound into decline.
The Bank estimates that the full impact of the decision is likely to start to be felt in prices and the economy only after four years.
Prior to the central bank's latest decision, calls for interest rate hikes had become increasingly vocal as inflation put pressure on households. Three policymakers called for a 0.5% rate hike in July.
Inflation eased to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June. However, according to the bank, this was expected and inflation will rise again in the coming months.
According to the bank, the two per cent overshoot was "entirely" due to the weak pound.
