NHS prescribes 10,000 controversial HIV drugs
From September, patients may be prescribed a "revolutionary" HIV prevention drug. The Supreme Court settled a dispute over the funding of the drug in England's National Health Service (NHS).
The NHS announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) will be prescribed to around 10,000 people during the first three-year trial. A drug taken before sexual intercourse has been found to reduce the risk of infection by about 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal upheld last year's Supreme Court ruling. It says the NHS is able to pay for PrEP, despite claiming that local authorities should fund it.
Simon Stevens, head of the NHS in England, called the decision announced on Thursday a "significant new intervention" and the National AIDS Agency described it as a "crucial moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start accepting registrations for the trial, which will expand to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full extent in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug taken before sexual intercourse that reduces the risk of infection.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infection in high-risk groups.
A medicine taken before intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during intercourse that prevent HIV infection.
The drug can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The target group for treatment includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people who have an HIV-positive partner who does not receive effective treatment.
The clinics will select eligible applicants for the trial from men, women and transgender people, as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral therapy for their condition.
People living in England and enrolled in general practitioner care can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme costs £10 million, and the NHS in England this week signed a procurement contract for medicines following an international tender.
The purpose of the trial is to assess the potential of PrEP by gathering extensive clinical evidence on targeting, taking and implementing treatment.
"This major new intervention should complement and enhance the diverse and increasingly effective approaches we already have to prevent HIV," says Stevens.
"It is yet another remarkable achievement in more than 30 years of fighting to solve one of humanity's greatest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," said Deborah Gold, executive director of the National AIDS Organization.
"If PrEP is properly targeted at those who need it and those at risk, it could have a game-changing impact on the HIV epidemic in England.
From September, those at risk will receive a medicine through an NHS-funded trial that they can decide on independently without having to consult a partner. It has an empowering effect that will improve the lives of so many people.
This was welcome news."
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the trial is launched quickly across the country and that no one at risk is left out," said Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP drug used in the trial has been procured and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand at-risk people from HIV infection."
"The launch of the PrEP trial is a welcome event that was needlessly prolonged by several months due to government delays," said shadow health minister Sharon Hodgson.
"We have evidence that the drug can have a game-changing effect on the work we do to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The trial will help us better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the experiment is launched as soon as possible throughout the country. In this way, we can protect those exposed to HIV and get one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
