Monty Widenius spends half of his time coding to keep the internet organized - the database he developed is used by companies such as Wikipedia and Google
Espoo-based company MariaDB is developing the "fastest growing open source database in the world".
Founded by coder entrepreneur Michael "Monty" Widenius, MariaDB's main product costs absolutely nothing to users and can be developed online by any skilled programmer.
For example, Google and Wikipedia are users of the Finnish database, but they are not necessarily paying customers.
Databases keep huge amounts of data organized and quickly accessible.
For example, if you use Linkedin, Twitter, or Booking.com, they use a database from MariaDB or MySQL.
"All information that is not in image format comes from the database, and the images are linked there," explains Widenius.
Widenius, who works as MariaDB's CTO, spends about half of his time coding.
A man who works remotely from Kauniainen does his part to ensure that the internet works smoothly.
Widenius developed MySQL, the world's most popular open source database, together with David Axmark from Sweden.
In 2008, technology company Sun bought MySQL for $7 billion, and a year later, software giant Oracle devoured Sun for $7.4 billion.
When the Oracle deal took place, a large number of MySQL developers announced they were leaving.
"They didn't want to work for Oracle, which didn't give a firm promise about the future of MySQL," Widenius recalls.
Already at this point, he had founded a company that began to develop MariaDB.
He didn't want his life's work to die.
I hired about twenty of the best developers from Sun to ensure that the continuity of the code is secured with the help of the same guys who created it.
Since MySQL is an open source database, MariaDB was able to develop its own branch.
The name just had to be changed.
A foundation was established to oversee the freedom of MariaDB code development.
"During MySQL, these verifications were not made," Widenius laments.
Although many people have heard about Widenius and MySQL's billion-dollar deal, few Finns know anything about MariaDB.
"In recent years, our growth rate has been around 50 percent per year," says Kenneth Paqvalén, CFO of MariaDB.
MariaDB, which focuses on growth, is not yet making a profit, and Paqvalén is tight-lipped about the company's key figures.
He reveals that MariaDB expects to receive orders worth EUR 20 million in the current financial year.
Since the database is free, the company has developed services around it that corporate customers are willing to pay for.
MariaDB also helps with the exchange of databases, which can be a task of more than a year if the customer has used a closed database.
Switching from MySQL to MariaDB is instantaneous because they are versions of each other.
Among others, the Spanish operator Telefónica and the largest bank in Southeast Asia, DBS, are paying customers of MariaDB.
The most popular cloud services such as Amazon's AWS, Microsoft's Azure, Alibaba's Cloud offer MariaDB to their customers.
At the same time, MariaDB is automatically distributed to new users in Linux operating system distributions, where MariaDB has largely replaced MySQL.
Even though we are a small company, we have connections to the biggest players.
"Our customers include the world's largest telecom operators, gaming companies, banks and even a few central banks," Paqvalén lists.
The database market is still dominated by giants such as Oracle, Microsoft, IBM and SAP with their closed databases.
Even for Oracle, MySQL is a modest side business compared to the company's traditional closed database.
Although according to research firm Gartner, the largest database companies have lost market share in recent years, in terms of revenue, players like MariaDB are still negligible, albeit fast-growing.
With a database market of about $50 billion, open source databases don't even reach a billion.
However, the weight of open source cannot be measured only in terms of money, since most users do not pay anything for this software.
Research firm Gartner predicts that by 2018, companies will already develop more than 70 percent of their internal applications on top of open databases.
In addition, more than half of the old databases would then have been replaced with open ones, or at least the migration would have begun.
Big companies don't get new customers because most choose open source next.
This has led to license fees for commercial databases skyrocketing.
Companies want to make as much money as before with fewer customers," Widenius says.
Since changing a closed database is a hassle, most client companies have obediently swallowed price increases.
"There are a lot of customers for whom migration is really difficult because their old applications and other things are closed in a closed database," Widenius says.
Still, he believes that customers are reaching their limit.
As license fees increase every year, sooner or later the customer switches to an open source database.
The price is 10-20 percent of the previous one, and the service is better because the customer can easily switch to another database if they wish.
In addition, many companies are facing major system changes as they move their operations to cloud services.
At the same time, many people change database software.
Last spring, MariaDB received a EUR 25 million loan from the European Investment Bank (EIB).
It was the largest growth financing ever granted by the EIB to the Nordic countries.
The company has around 115 employees worldwide and plans to hire more now.
One of the reasons for the EIB's financing was the impact of MariaDB on public IT procurement.
The company has public sector customers in countries such as the UK and Germany.
The public sector in Europe pays billions of euros annually for databases.
"Many countries want to switch to open source solutions and thus use tax money more efficiently," Paqvalén says.
Widenius is annoyed by how money is wasted in Finland, for example, on closed healthcare systems, when open systems are cheaper and the client is not at the mercy of one software company.
Some people say that open source is an ideology, but I think it's a better way to make code.
The community helps and does things that it cannot invent or be able to do.
The 55-year-old Widenius is, along with another Finnish Linux developer, Linus Torvalds, one of the best-known promoters of open source.
Widenius helps other companies develop functional business models on top of open source.
