How did one activist learn to answer the question: who do the streets belong to?
Brittany Ferrell was deeply shocked on 09/08/2014.
He had arrived in New York the day before from his home in St. Louis and was sitting on the bed of his Airbnb apartment, scrolling through Facebook on his phone.
That's when she noticed a message from a high school friend:
"The police just killed an 18-year-old youth, and his body is still on the street."
Confused, she noticed that no one else had posted the same information on her feed. That's why he shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
His timeline featured numerous retweets from a user @TheePharoah.
The username belongs to the St. Louis-based rapper who tweeted in real-time about Michael Brown's death. Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man, had been shot dead by white police in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user in question had also posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body on the street, where it was left for four hours.
"This is incredible," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
He put his phone away. When he returned to Twitter later that night, there were reports that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
Users posted pictures of police barracks and screaming people, as well as a man claiming to be Brown's father, carrying a sign that read, "My unarmed son was just killed by Ferguson police!"
Ferrell watched real-time video footage of police standing in front of protesters with a barking dog.
He says he also saw a video of another police officer cocking his rifle and shouting, "I'm going to kill all of you... animals."
"This is not normal," Ferrell remembers saying.
"It wasn't the kind of murder we're already used to and could be called typical.
That's when I felt cold shivers.
I was angry and crying."
He booked a return flight home the next day.
The plane landed at eleven o'clock in the evening. Ferrell went to pick up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided they would leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next nearly three years has been the subject of a documentary called "Whose Streets?". It premiered in cinemas on 11.8.2017.
The film is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, and strength and resilience from the point of view of the local people who took to the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove toward Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a floral dress and matching crown, they had another conversation about "what it's like to live black and under what circumstances." They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
"Remember when I told you how blacks have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"I couldn't help but take my daughter with me," Ferrell later recounted.
"Today's events are... the culmination of events from the past.
My daughter has the right to know that and grow into it.
They need to be prepared for activism and organization, but they also need to know the different layers and circumstances of the experience of living as a black person. And he needs to know what we have to do to liberate, to free ourselves.
While I've thankfully been able to protect her from blatant racism, she's still like other black girls.
I feel like I would hurt him if I protected him from reality."
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, located across from the police station. It became a camp for activists as they waited for information on the handling of the case and eventually learned that no charges would be brought against the police.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made packed lunches.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
"My activism changed completely after August 9th," she says. While attending the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was president of the Association of Minority Nursing Students. At the time, she focused on food justice and health inequalities in Black communities.
"I had no experience of organizing.
Somehow it just happened."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the documentary's assistant director, at an evening protest.
Folayan said he and cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "simply wanted to tell" what was happening.
Doubt crept into Ferrell's mind. He asked, "Do you really want to tell what is happening, or do you want a story that you can use to your advantage?"
The suspicion stemmed from the countless times people had appeared in the local community, usually white, who simply wanted to profit from its difficulties and perseverance.
"We had heard that those born and raised in Ferguson did not have a common voice," Folayan said in a recent interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted assistant director Damon Davis, known for his activism with death row inmates.
Davis' involvement led Ferrell to join the project with six other locals. The film crew followed the events in the years following Brown's shooting.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, we speak," Davis says.
"For me, the most important thing was how the local people are portrayed in the film, because I'm portrayed the same way."
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences because they wanted to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader, but about a community." However, Ferrell proved to be the most open of the subjects.
That's why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs as he explains how it felt to see the film for the first time.
"But I realized that this work and the humane portrayal of blacks requires a certain vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrell's story recaps and refocuses on the role of black queer women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born on social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after police shot and killed a black teenage boy, Trayvon Martin, in 2012. Two of the movement's three founders identify with queer identities.
"The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going," Ferrell says. "That's because we have to fight constantly on many fronts.
Black queer women have had to endure everything."
Folayan agrees, "The movement is really run by black women, including a lot of queer women."
However, he emphasizes that Ferrell was not chosen for the documentary "as an end in itself" because of his queer identity.
"He got the energy going," Folaya says.
"However, it is no coincidence that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is conveyed on screen."
News crews have long since left Ferguson, but relations between the community and police remain strained.
Ferrell still has two and a half years left on parole. He was convicted of blocking a motorway during a demonstration.
His description of the sociopolitical climate in his home neighbourhood is short and to the point: "A mess."
Yet he still relies on a slogan he memorized on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We can only lose our chains."
Matching resemblance: artist creates portraits of Chelsea Manning's DNA
The Fridman Gallery in New York has faces hanging in the middle of the exhibition space – white, black and brown faces that resemble each other on closer inspection.
These 30 works are portraits by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg based on DNA samples taken from Chelsea Manning's cheek and hair.
Manning sent samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where he was serving his 35-year sentence. Manning was convicted of leaking classified diplomatic telegrams to WikiLeaks.
Dewey-Hagborg's exhibition A Becoming Resemblance opened on 2.8.2017.
It is based on two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg and Manning. Dewey-Hagborg's work combines technology, information technology and art. Manning is a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose prison sentence was commuted by Barack Obama on the third-to-last day of his term.
Dewey-Hagborg algorithmically analyzed Manning's DNA and created 30 portraits based on his genetic data. They are a sharp, if somewhat theoretical, statement on the modifiability, ambiguity, and cause-effect relationships and identity behind DNA data.
Chelsea Manning, born Bradley Edward, has openly stated that she has identified with women since puberty. He was found guilty of 20 offences in 2013, including violation of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one photo of Manning, who had been sentenced to prison: a grainy, black-and-white selfie of an embarrassed Manning sitting in the driver's seat of a car. She wears a platinum blonde wig, which became her hallmark.
Dewey-Hagborg had the hugely popular Stranger Visions project behind her in 2015, which she carried out in 2012.
In it, he created portraits based on forensic data. He obtained DNA data from cigarette butts and chewing gums, for example, and created images of what the people in question might have looked like.
Then the artist received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning and needed a picture for their story," Dewey-Hagborg told a news conference for the new show.
Manning could not be visited or photographed in prison. So the magazine contacted Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in making a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse unexpectedly became correspondent friends. They wrote to each other for a couple of years.
They even made a comic book together, Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo. It depicted a future in which the president would have commuted Chelsea's sentence and he would get to see the show.
In reality, Obama shortened Manning's sentence just days after the comic book was published. It was a fortunate coincidence after seven tough years in a military prison in Kansas.
It's also impressive that the exhibition opens right now, when Donald Trump is waging his own war against whistleblowers and transgender soldiers, finding more and more ways on Twitter to reinforce the strong divisions he actually needed to defuse.
Dewey-Hagborg believes that "everything has a purpose."
On the wall of the gallery is a statement by the artist and underneath it is a large autograph of Manning, where the dot of the i in the surname is the heart. In his statement, the artist calls for an end to "the automatic divisions on which gender, race, sexuality and culture are based."
On the opposite wall is a sequence of Manning's DNA: a long string of letters C, G and A written in pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or nucleotide, as the artist's scientific definition goes – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we all are, at least in terms of biology.
"I hope that my exhibition will help people understand that we are genetically equal and that genetic information is very personal and open to interpretation," Dewey-Hagborg says. The exhibition also features his video work Spurious Memories from 2007.
"DNA tells countless stories. 30 of them are on display here."
The last work in the exhibition is in its own room: a page from Manning and Dewey-Hagborg's comic book.
In it, Manning's figure emerges from prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
"If they can silence you, they've won," the image reads.
"Never be silent."
"The text is from a letter I received from Manning," the Philadelphia-native artist says.
"It's so impressive that I still get chills."
Contrary to what was portrayed in the comic book, Manning has yet to see the show. When Manning arrives, he is greeted by faces based on his own genetic information, like a crowd of protesters in the middle of the showroom.
It is intentional, like everything else in this exhibition: for example, Manning's DNA sequence is written in pencil at a height equal to his height (157.5 cm).
"The face used to be on the wall, but I wanted to give it the feel of a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg says.
"I wanted to describe the mass movement created by Chelsea, which was also behind his release."
