The Birth of a Comic Book: The Story of a Castle
Small Scotney Castle in County Kent is now known for the Squeeze music video and as Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
However, it has 700 years of turbulent history behind it. Now this picturesque castle in the Bewl River Valley is the subject of a comic book by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer fond of old documents.
"I love being able to study a text written by someone who died over 300 years ago," Rhodes says wistfully.
"I feel a personal connection when I hold a letter in my hand."
Rhodes' book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families who lived in Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from the British National Library. The project was emotional.
"I was moved to tears when I noticed a thumbprint in the letter. The letter was written by a double agent who worked for the Jacobites in the 1700s," Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprint!
And the letters smell like smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the fragrance makes the reader feel that he himself is on the spot.
I love archives!"
Fascinated by old documents, the author was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust and the National Arts Council of England, which seemed too good to be true. He admits that he couldn't wait to stay at the castle a little longer than he would have liked.
He spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures and rarities such as hyena heads hung on walls and bottles that had been in moats for centuries.
He toured the ruins and grounds of the old castle and talked with rangers, gardeners and sometimes artists illustrating the book.
In the evenings, he "took whiskey and began writing."
Scotney's closer history is relatively unknown, as the castle only passed entirely to the National Trust after the death of its last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the foundation's staff was just beginning to go through the archives. Rhodes describes that archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking all the excess to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the times of the English Empire, and maps of who owned what. "You would think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "Here, however, families even fought over one birch.
It occurred to me that we shouldn't let it be."
Some of the stories in the book progress from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer. It tells the story of a man who, shortly after the castle was completed, joins the English Peasant Revolt in 1381.
"The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex book mentions that there was a riot at the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
