Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a digestive system nightmare.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet high in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects approximately 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 people in the United Kingdom. It causes stomach cramps, bloating, frequent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with irritable bowel syndrome are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that tryptophan, an essential amino acid contained in the protein, helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to study leader Marco Colonna, immune cells guard the gut and ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food do not enter the body.
Cells that cause inflammation are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance drops too close to inflammation, irritable bowel syndrome can result.
The experiments found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are present in mice that have certain bacteria in their intestines.
This bacterium needs tryptophan for immune cells to appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between the bacterium Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal gut microbiome," Professor Colonna says.
"The more tryptophan in the diet of mice, the more such immune cells they had."
If the same works in humans, a combination of Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria and a tryptophan-rich diet can strengthen gut tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
In studying immune cells that strengthen tolerance, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same mouse species, which were kept separate from another group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiome of mice, that is, the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the digestive tract.
When the gut DNA of the mice was examined, six species of bacteria were found that were present in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice that grew up in a sterile environment and did not have a gut microbiome and did not develop immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in a liquid and transplanted small amounts of fluid – without bacteria – into immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells evolved into cells that strengthen tolerance.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of cells that strengthen tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When the amount of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells fell by half.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same resilience-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus reuteri cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been found in people with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to promote the development of these cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," says Cervantes-Barragan.
"High levels of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their generalization."
