White House exhibit cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
The White House's decision last month to fly a naval helicopter to the White House's South Turf for an event showcasing American production cost taxpayers $24,000. This information appears from military documents obtained by TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is referred to as Marine One when the President is on board. It was the main attraction of an event held at the White House on 17/07/2017 to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a group of White House officials reviewed the products from all 50 states.
In addition to the Connecticut-made helicopter, a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi were on display.
The White House military office had requested a helicopter on the scene by mission-specific order just about 36 hours before it landed on a southern turf for the "extraordinary" event. This is evident from the documents of the HMX-1 helicopter squadron of the Navy.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an exceptional event that gets a lot of visibility," the HMX-1 unit commander wrote the day before the incident in an email to his superior, who is Deputy Commandant of Naval Air Command.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive at the southern grass field on 17.7. at seven in the morning and the event would start at three in the afternoon. The helicopter would only leave the scene after the grass field was cleared between six and nine o'clock in the evening.
In addition, the message mentioned that if the helicopter's departure from the White House was delayed, another crew would be needed due to service time constraints.
The original crew was in the helicopter for the duration of the incident, and unit security personnel were at the helicopter while it was on the ground.
Documents obtained by TIME magazine do not indicate whether another crew was ultimately needed.
The Hatch Act in the United States prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 inquired whether the incident violated the law.
"One of our questions was whether this violated the Hatch Act. We were told not to break," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you can contribute," the deputy commandant replied.
Made in America was an official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president spoke in favor of health care reform being considered by the Senate at the time, as well as looser state regulation.
The use of the Marine One helicopter and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must wear them on their travels,
But using them only for photos is unusual.
Trump's actions attracted attention in February when Air Force One rolled into the background of a presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized the use of his predecessor's presidential plane on Twitter.
"The White House is very pleased with Made in America, which showcased products made from American materials by American employees from all 50 states," said White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 unit crews regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and practice on a southern turf field to bring the president to the White House with centimeter accuracy.
While Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings at the White House.
According to one official, flights to Made in America were part of the crew's monthly training quota.
The unit's helicopters also flew for 11 hours that day on "non-presidential support missions."
According to the White House, the incident did not incur any other costs for taxpayers.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in organizing a demonstration of the helicopter on the White House South Lawn.
HMX-1 has no records of flights related to presidential duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the cost of the event.
According to the Department of Defense's 2017 hourly rates, the compensation level for a VH-3D helicopter is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 documents, flights from the Quantico base in Virginia to the White House and back took a total of one hour.
According to the White House, the operating costs of the helicopter are significantly lower.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation is misleading," Walters says.
"The estimated level of compensation includes staffing, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs, which are taken into account in the annual allocations."
According to a 2015 study by RAND, compensation levels do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time of the incident, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of a helicopter at the event.
"The idea is to showcase American production," Spicer said.
"I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security, employing probably hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think that, like most Americans, we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that many Americans have worked so hard for.
It's perfectly appropriate to bring that up."
It's not clear if Trump was in the helicopter during the incident, but at least he sat in the driver's seat of the fire truck.
