Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar's transfer three years ago?
LaLiga may regret its interest in Marco Verrattin
Paris Saint-Germain will not give up pursuing Neymar after paying a transfer fee of £189m to terminate his contract. But did PSG warn Barcelona about a record-breaking transfer three years ago?
The sensational move is the most talked about case of the summer. The French Ligue 1 football league team is ready to break the world record for transfer sums. The previous record was less than half as low: it came about when Paul Pogba returned to Manchester United for a transfer fee of £89 million.
After the transfer, Neymar will become the most expensive footballer in the world and also the highest-paid professional athlete in the world, with PSG offering him a weekly salary of more than £500,000 after tax.
Barcelona are known to be furious with PSG's actions and the way Neymar has forcibly left the club. A source close to Barcelona says the club have taken very good care of Neymar since he arrived at Santos in 2013.
Did the PSG chairman warn the football world about this move three years ago?
When Manchester City announced their interest in Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi warned clubs aiming for PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they want our players, we will be their opponent and we will contact their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they go after our players, they will face the consequences."
Barcelona appear to have been guilty of just that: they expressed interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verrattti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear that they would not allow the Italian to leave under any circumstances. It could well be that Barcelona will lose their star player Neymar as a result.
