NOW: Trump's hyped phone calls were fabricated - White House spokesman: 'I wouldn't say it was a lie'
The White House admits that the two calls mentioned by US President Donald Trump never happened, according to the New York Times.
Trump's praised phone calls with both Mexico's president and the leader of the Boy Scout organization have turned out to be fabricated.
White House spokeswoman Sarah Huckabee Sanders confirmed that there had been no phone calls.
However, he said Trump wasn't lying.
According to Sanders, many of the scouts' leaders spoke to Trump in person, and Trump had spoken with Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto at the G20 summit in Hamburg.
I wouldn't say it was a lie, it's a pretty tough accusation.
Those conversations happened, they didn't just happen on the phone, they happened face-to-face," Sanders reasoned.
The speech to the scouts aroused outrage
Trump said Monday that the Mexican president called him and praised Trump's success in stamping out illegal immigration.
According to Trump, Pena Nieto said that few people come across Mexico's southern border anymore because they know the trip will stop at the U.S. border anyway.
On Wednesday, the Mexican government released a statement saying that the call in question had not taken place.
On Tuesday, Politico released a full version of Trump's interview with The Wall Street Journal.
In it, Trump touted his speech at a major rally of the National Scout Association in West Virginia.
I got a call from the leader of the Boy Scouts, he said it was the finest speech ever given to them.
They were very grateful," Trump said.
On Wednesday, the Boy Scout organization said it was not aware of any of its leaders' phone calls to Trump.
According to the release, an earlier statement by the organization's director, Michael Surbaugh, who had apologized to the scouts for Trump's speech, speaks for itself.
Trump's speech at the Boy Scout meeting caused a lot of astonishment, as it was exceptionally political considering the nature of the event.
Among other things, he praised the results of last autumn's presidential election.
